// 000  000
// |    |
// npc  string

// dca_BDDELANC.d
@0 = ~Fine. I'll be off.~
// Replaces vanilla "...Very well. What do you require of me?"
@1 = ~...Very well. What else have you learned?~
@2 = ~An ugly task, but I will see it done.~
@3 = ~I want no part in victory purchased with needless suffering.~
@4 = ~I kill when it suits me, but I will not play poisoner for you. Press me no further.~
// From vanilla "Given a choice between victory and honor, I know which I'll choose. I can see you'll not be persuaded entirely by reason—given your reputation, I can't say I'm surprised. Perhaps you are open to compromise. Would it change your mind if I told you the poison wasn't lethal?"
@5 = ~Perhaps you are open to compromise. Would it change your mind if I told you the poison wasn't lethal?~ [DCDEL01]
@6 = ~What is going on here?~
@7 = ~I appreciate the distinction, but my answer is no.~
@8 = ~I agree. Caelar's terms are generous only if her purpose is harmless—and she has given us no cause to believe that.~

// dca_BDNEDERL.d
@1000 = ~The information sounds promising, but was there truly no other means to obtain it?~
@1001 = ~I trust this is not your first recourse.~
@1002 = ~Even so, I would hear the rest. What else have you learned?~
@1003 = ~Safe from whom, Nederlok? The woman who promised to return me unharmed, or the man who said he would happily see me sacrificed?~

// dca_BDMURS.d
@2000 = ~Hold your clubs! Yes, we ARE from the crusade, but we are here to help you.~
@2001 = ~I thought there might be something here worth stealing.~

// dca_BDARBING.d
@3000 = ~I know good counsel when I hear it. Goodbye.~

// dca_DYINGM.d
// Replaces vanilla "I can't understand you. Are you all right? What is that horrible smell?"
@3000 = ~I can't understand you. Are you all right?~
@3001 = ~I think we should leave.~

// dca_BDBELLOW.d
@4000 = ~A touching reunion with the surface, no doubt. Farewell.~
// From vanilla "If you gotta mosey off, I understand. We'll be here if you need anythin'."
@4001 = ~If you gotta mosey off, I understand.~ [DCBLW01]
// From vanilla "*gasp* I thought we'd never get back up! Sure is good to see the surface again."
@4002 = ~Sure is good to see the surface again.~ [DCBLW02]
@4003 = ~I'll leave you to enjoy the fresh cave air, then.~

// dca_BDSHAPUR.d
@5000 = ~I came here by mistake. I will leave at once.~
@5001 = ~I have no part in this strife. Finish it without me.~
@5002 = ~Then I withdraw. Let your choices claim you.~
@5003 = ~If you are so intent on dying, then so be it.~

// dca_BDTHERLI.d
@5004 = ~I merely hoped talking might spare a great deal of bleeding.~

// dca_BDPWATER.d
// From vanilla "A wizard tried to bind them to his will. I put an end to his evil."
@6000 = ~A wizard tried to bind them to his will. He will trouble you no more.~  
@6001 = ~Keep it. I only did what the moment required.~

// dca_BDKHARMY.d
@7000 = ~Of course. I'll find a way to free you.~
@7001 = ~~
// From vanilla "Those spikes in the floor were designed to shoot up and impale you. One pull of that lever across the room and I'd rid the world of three crusaders. I'll tell your fellows the cultists killed you."
@7002 = ~Those spikes in the floor were designed to shoot up and impale you. One pull of that lever across the room and I'd rid the world of three crusaders.~
@7003 = ~I am merely considering all options. Now, how might we free them?~
@7004 = ~I will not take the lives of helpless prisoners. But neither will I open the door for crusaders. The cages stay shut.~
@7005 = ~Letting crusaders live is a risk I am not willing to take. Say whatever prayers you know.~
@7006 = ~Stand aside. I want to see what the spikes do.~
@7007 = ~I was merely thinking out loud. How would I go about freeing you?~
@7008 = ~If you serve the crusade, I cannot spare you. Say whatever prayers you know.~
@7009 = ~Beg louder. I want to hear it when I pull the lever.~
@7010 = ~I will have to think about this.~
// From vanilla "The Missing Patrol
// 
// My next task is to take the crusader leader's badge back to the crusader camp. [...]"
@7011 = ~The Missing Patrol

I decided to leave the crusaders in their cages.

I found the missing crusader patrol. If I can free them, I might be able to gain access to the crusader camp. Someone on this level must have a key to their cage. There's also a switch on the wall and giant spikes poised beneath the cage. If I kill the crusaders, I might be able to convince the camp guard that they were dead when I found them.~
// From vanilla "The Missing Patrol
// 
// My next task is to take the crusader leader's badge back to the crusader camp. [...]"
@7012 = ~The Missing Patrol

I can take the crusader leader's badge back to the crusader camp and lie about what happened.

I had meant neither to rescue nor kill them, but a nearby lever proved too tempting. When I pulled it, spikes shot up through the cages and impaled the crusaders, killing all three of them.~
// From vanilla "You wear crusader colors. I have no interest in helping you. In fact, I should kill you right now."
@7013 = ~You wear crusader colors. I have no interest in helping you. Farewell.~
@7014 = ~Why free you when I can kill you instead?~
@7015 = ~I will not free crusaders. Remain where you are. Farewell.~
// Replaces vanilla "The Missing Patrol
// 
// My next task is to take the crusader leader's badge back to the crusader camp. [...]"
@7016 = ~The Missing Patrol

I can take the crusader leader's badge back to the crusader camp and lie about what happened.

I found the missing crusader patrol imprisoned by cultists in the ruined temple. I killed them by pulling a lever which caused spikes to shoot up and impale all the crusaders in the cage. Gruesome.~
@7017 = ~The Missing Patrol

I decided to leave the crusaders in their cages.~
@8000 = ~I am not here to keep you company, and my name is not yours to know. I will speak to you no further.~
@8001 = ~I will not free you.~
@8002 = ~Rest, then. I have no more questions for the moment.~
@8003 = ~The Eyeless Priestess

I decided to leave Madele imprisoned.~
@8004 = ~The Eyeless Priestess

I freed Madele from her imprisonment and ordered her to amend for her misdeeds.~
@8005 = ~The Eyeless Priestess

I freed Madele from her imprisonment.~
@8006 = ~I have nothing to say to you.~
@8007 = ~I have nothing more to say to you.~
@8008 = ~That is all I need to know. Farewell.~

// dca_BDSLUG.d
@9000 = ~Fine. No talk, then.~
@9001 = ~How did you end up here?~
@9002 = ~I have to go now. Farewell.~
@9003 = ~I see. Well, I had best get a move on. Farewell.~

// dca_dragonspear_trolls.d
@10000 = ~I'll do what I can, but keep your claws to yourselves.~
@10001 = ~I have a castle to take. Convince me this is worth the risk.~
@10002 = ~I'll leave you here for now. Free trolls may do more harm than good in this chaos.~
@10003 = ~Beg to someone else, beast. I like you penned.~
@10004 = ~I have no time for this. There is a battle raging, in case you hadn't noticed.~
// From vanilla (59804):
// "The Siege of Dragonspear
// 
// I left the trolls penned up, though I can always return and release them to create havoc.
// 
// I didn't want to leave the troll penned up like that, but perhaps a wild troll running amok isn't a good idea at the moment."
@10005 = ~The Siege of Dragonspear

I told the trolls I would free them if I could.

The creatures begged for release from their pen, saying they had been taken, tormented, and forced to fight for the crusade. I should try to help them.~
// From vanilla, as above
@10006 = ~The Siege of Dragonspear

The captive trolls offered to fight the crusaders if I release them.

They say they were captured, hurt, and forced to fight for the crusade. If I can loose them safely, their anger may prove useful against Dragonspear's defenders.~
// From vanilla, as above
@10007 = ~The Siege of Dragonspear

I left the trolls penned up, though I can always return and release them to create havoc.~
// From vanilla "Please. You kill Gnarg. Let us out and we help you fight him friends."
@10008 = ~You kill Gnarg. Let us out and we help you fight him friends.~ [DCTHD01]
@10009 = ~I'll do what I can.~
@10010 = ~I have a castle to take. How is this worth the risk?~
@10011 = ~I'll leave them where they are for now. Free trolls may do more harm than good in this chaos.~
@10012 = ~I see no problem here. Only trolls where trolls should be.~
@10013 = ~I have a castle to take. If anyone can tell me how this would be worth the risk, I am all ears.~
// From vanilla (259805):
// "The Siege of Dragonspear
// 
// The Siege of Dragonspear
// 
// I freed the trolls to wreak vengeance on the crusaders.
// 
// The crusaders stole the trolls from their homes and used them for shock troops. Now the trolls are free, and the crusade will pay the price for its slaver ways."
@10014 = ~The Siege of Dragonspear

I let the trolls loose to turn on the crusaders.

The crusaders had captured the trolls and used them as shock troops. Once freed, the trolls turned their anger on their captors.~

// dca_ASHATI.d
@11000 = ~If your cause is righteous, then call off your soldiers. My side will stand down if yours do the same.~
@11001 = ~You are right. I am a child of Bhaal, and I embrace it. I came here for murder. Only a fool would think I would join your side.~
@11002 = ~A sensible offer. Call me intrigued.~
@11003 = ~This may prove amusing. I accept.~
@11004 = ~No. One death is a poor harvest. Let the field have its fill.~
// From vanilla "Champions of light! You see now the cowardice, the duplicity of those who challenge the Lady! Slay the
// unbeliever! Slay them all, in Caelar's name!" (61340)
@11005 = ~Champions of light! You see now the duplicity of those who challenge the Lady! Slay the unbeliever! Slay them all, in Caelar's name!~ [DCASH01]
@11006 = ~No bargain, then. If we fight, we fight as war demands.~

// dca_BDAUN.d
@12000 = ~What is done is done. Caelar will answer for her crimes.~
@12001 = ~You are not to blame for what was done in your name. But many suffered for it.~
@12002 = ~You should be more thankful. Caelar purchased your life with a mountain of corpses.~
@12003 = ~Spare me the family reckoning.~
@12004 = ~No child should have been set to guard such knowledge. Whatever followed, that fault was theirs.~
@12005 = ~A fitting lesson. Pity it failed to take.~
@12006 = ~But the cage did not hold you forever.~
@12007 = ~So a tome transported Caelar to Avernus. What happened next?~
